<div>
<b>Package Comments:</b>
<ul>
<li class="comment"><b>bk</b> (2010-09-24, 5 points):<br/>Works perfect for me as I know jQuery syntax. <br />Needs a better information how to install. I'm on windows and not used to install with setup.py. But a great project. </li>
<li class="comment"><b>nyteschayde</b> (2010-11-07, 5 points):<br/>Excellent tool. Makes working with HTML strings a breeze </li>
<li class="comment"><b>loveencounterflow</b> (2010-11-28, 0 points):<br/>a project with an interesting and useful goal. but i warn against the dependency on lxml. i have known that library since 2004 and it has been buggy ever since. you can easy_install lxml using python 3.1 alright, but that will generate a syntax error (but leave the files in site-packages). you can then apply 2to3 conversion to the lxml folder, but that will still leave you with at least one file with a faulty indentation. you can fix that but that will still leave you with a bug in lxml/cssselect.py. you can wade through the horrible code and fix that bug or say rm -r lxml which is what i did. even if you should get lxml working you will still have horrible code on your machine. and even if lxml should work it will through up at any minuscule unevenness in the html, which is said, since validating html does almost not exist in the world. i had to wrap my html into a nonsense div, parse it with BeautifulSoup and write the repaired html out again to make lxml accept it. you're probably better off rolling your own jQuery-like library. </li>
</ul>

